explanation:
OS_mut_sem_prop_t: Needed to see the definition of the pointed-to type (fields, whether name is a char[] or char*, sizes, and which fields are written). This determines whether the function actually modifies the object (so the pointer cannot be const) or could be treated as read-only.

OS_common_record_t: Required to know the types and const-qualification of record->name_entry and record->creator that are read and copied into mut_prop; also to check whether record fields are const-qualified (affects whether copying from a const source would require casts).

OS_object_token_t: The local token variable is passed by address to other routines; its type/definition is needed to determine whether &token is compatible with const-qualified pointer parameters and whether token is modified by callees (impacts const-qualification possibilities).

OS_CHECK_POINTER: Macro/utility that checks the mut_prop parameter; its definition may perform casts or other operations that affect how mut_prop is treated and whether a const-qualified pointer would be acceptable.

OS_ObjectIdGetById: Prototype is needed to know how it initializes/uses the token (e.g., whether it takes a non-const pointer to token) and whether it imposes any constness constraints on parameters returned/modified by this call.

OS_ObjectIdRelease: Prototype is needed to see if it takes a pointer to token and whether that API requires non-const token handling (informs whether token must be mutable and whether passing &token to other functions implies mutability requirements).

OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: Macro used to obtain record from OS_global_mutex_table; its expansion/type dictates whether the returned record pointer is const-qualified or not, which affects whether data copied from record would require casting and whether mut_prop must be non-const.

OS_global_mutex_table: The table symbol/type is required because OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET may depend on its type to yield a const or non-const record pointer; this influences const-correctness of reads from record.

OS_MutSemGetInfo_Impl: Prototype shows how mut_prop is used by the implementation (whether it is passed as a const pointer or modified). If the Impl function modifies mut_prop, the parameter cannot be const; if it only reads, that could affect whether const qualification is possible at the API level.
